Sed si quis nunc Valerium appellans incasu vocandi secundum id prae· ceptum Nigidii acuerit primam, non aberit, quin rideatur. ‘Summum’ autem ‘tonum’ προσῳδίαν acutam dicit et, quem accentum nos dicimus, ‘voculationem' appellat. This fragment of Nigidius Figulus seems to be a protest against the introduction of the Greek accentual theory into Rome.

, His doctrine that every syllable has a stress is directly opposed to that of Cicero, but is in perfect accord with the tripudic theory. It is natural that in the casas vocandi there should be a strong stress on the first syllable. Fortunately, Aulus Gellius has preserved this fragment to ηε, although he does not agree with the doctrine it teaches. For further observations on Nigidius Figulus, see FitzHugh, I. R, p. 103.
